INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b41ad37b-fdf3-4efb-80eb-30778bd13684',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Cargo.lock — Pinning, Auditing, and Staying Ahead of Vulnerabilities$escape$,
  $escape$Cargo.lock pins every dependency to an exact version, including transitive ones. For binaries, commit it — `cargo build` will reproduce identical artifacts across machines and CI. For libraries, don't commit it; downstream consumers resolve their own dependency graph. Versioning in `Cargo.toml` uses SemVer with caret requirements by default: `tokio = "1"` allows any `1.x.y` but locks the major version. Use `cargo update -p tokio` to bump a single crate without touching the rest of the lock file.

For auditing, `cargo audit` (from the `cargo-audit` crate) queries the RustSec Advisory Database against your `Cargo.lock`. It surfaces CVEs, unsoundness reports, and yanked versions. Integrate it into CI with a non-zero exit on findings. `cargo deny` goes further — it enforces license allowlists, bans specific crates, and checks for duplicate dependency versions that bloat your binary. Together, these tools give you a reproducible, auditable supply chain without leaving the Cargo ecosystem.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install auditing tools
cargo install cargo-audit cargo-deny

# Audit against RustSec Advisory Database
cargo audit

# Update a single dependency without touching others
cargo update -p serde

# deny.toml — enforce license and ban rules
# [bans]
# deny = ["openssl"]  # force rustls instead

# [licenses]
# allow = ["MIT", "Apache-2.0", "ISC"]

cargo deny check$escape$,
