INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a76519b9-5f29-40c3-98a0-b64344285ec7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Type System — Zero-Cost Generics, Inference, and Why You Rarely Write Types Twice$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's type system is static and affine — every value has a single, compile-time-known type, and the borrow checker enforces ownership on top of that. Unlike dynamic languages where type errors surface at runtime, Rust's monomorphization means generics are fully resolved at compile time with no boxing overhead. Write `fn largest<T: PartialOrd>(list: &[T]) -> &T` once; the compiler stamps out specialized versions per concrete type used — zero vtable, zero indirection.

Type inference via Hindley-Milner lets you omit most annotations. `let mut map = HashMap::new();` is valid as long as the compiler can infer key/value types from usage downstream. Where inference fails, turbofish syntax pins the type at the call site: `Vec::<i32>::new()`.

Trait bounds replace interfaces: `T: Display + Clone` is a compile-time contract, not a runtime check. Combined with `impl Trait` in return position, you get static dispatch without naming the concrete type — useful for closures and iterator chains where the type is unutterable. Unlike Go's interfaces or Java's generics (which erase types), Rust generics are reified, making them both safer and faster.$escape$,
  $escape$use std::fmt::Display;

fn print_largest<T: PartialOrd + Display>(list: &[T]) -> &T {
    let mut largest = &list[0];
    for item in list.iter() {
        if item > largest {
            largest = item;
        }
    }
    println!("Largest: {largest}");
    largest
}

fn main() {
    let numbers = vec![34, 50, 25, 100, 65];
    print_largest(&numbers); // monomorphized to i32 at compile time

    let chars = vec!['y', 'm', 'a', 'q'];
    print_largest(&chars); // separate monomorphized version for char
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
