INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd39a2854-2230-4412-8a8d-0139f4cfe562',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Ownership Model — Why You Don't Need a GC$escape$,
  $escape$Most languages manage heap memory with a garbage collector — a runtime that periodically scans for unreachable allocations. Rust eliminates the GC entirely by enforcing ownership at compile time. Every value has exactly one owner; when that owner goes out of scope, `drop()` is called automatically, freeing the memory. No runtime overhead, no stop-the-world pauses.

Stack vs heap matters here. Primitives like `i32` and `bool` live on the stack — zero allocation cost, popped when the frame exits. `Box<T>`, `Vec<T>`, and `String` allocate on the heap and carry an RAII guard: the destructor runs the moment the binding is dropped.

Borrowing extends this without copying. A `&T` reference lets you read heap data without taking ownership; `&mut T` gives exclusive write access. The borrow checker enforces that no mutable reference coexists with any other reference — at compile time, not runtime. This prevents use-after-free, double-free, and data races structurally, not through sanitizers or GC heuristics. The invariant is: one owner, many readers OR one writer, zero readers.$escape$,
  $escape$fn main() {
    // Stack allocated — dropped when `x` goes out of scope
    let x: i32 = 42;

    // Heap allocated — Box<T> owns the allocation
    let boxed: Box<i32> = Box::new(100);

    // Borrow: read-only reference, no ownership transfer
    let r: &i32 = &x;
    println!("ref: {r}");

    // Exclusive mutable borrow
    let mut v: Vec<i32> = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let first: &mut i32 = &mut v[0];
    *first += 10;
    println!("{:?}", v); // [11, 2, 3]

    // `boxed` and `v` dropped here — heap freed, no GC needed
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
