INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cff08d67-b0b9-42c9-81ba-6773661b8969',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust Concurrency — Threads, Async, and Why the Compiler Is Your Race-Condition Detector$escape$,
  $escape$Rust offers two concurrency primitives: OS threads via `std::thread::spawn` and async tasks via `tokio::spawn` (or `async-std`). Unlike Go's goroutines, Rust has no built-in runtime — you pick one. Tokio is the de facto choice, running an M:N thread pool under the hood.

The real differentiator is the type system. `Send` marks types safe to move across threads; `Sync` marks types safe to share by reference. Violating either is a compile error, not a runtime panic. This eliminates entire classes of data races before your code ships.

Shared mutable state requires `Arc<Mutex<T>>` (threads) or `Arc<tokio::sync::Mutex<T>>` (async). For message-passing, `std::sync::mpsc` or Tokio's `mpsc`/`broadcast` channels mirror the actor pattern without a full framework like Actix.

Async functions return `impl Future` — zero-cost, no heap allocation unless you box them. `.await` yields control cooperatively; CPU-bound work should move to `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` to avoid starving the executor. Rust gives you the primitives; the borrow checker enforces the discipline.$escape$,
  $escape$use tokio::sync::mpsc;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let (tx, mut rx) = mpsc::channel::<String>(32);

    tokio::spawn(async move {
        tx.send("event from task".to_string()).await.unwrap();
    });

    while let Some(msg) = rx.recv().await {
        println!("Received: {msg}");
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
