INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '02166e07-0fbe-4b04-8487-0ee96a22bbd8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Standard Library — What's In the Box vs What You'll Need a Crate For$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's std is intentionally lean. You get collections (HashMap, BTreeMap, Vec, VecDeque), threading primitives (Mutex, RwLock, Arc, mpsc channels), I/O traits (Read, Write, BufReader), and basic networking (TcpStream, UdpSocket). That's more than C's stdlib but far less than Go's.

What's missing is deliberate. There's no async runtime in std — you choose tokio, async-std, or smol. No HTTP client or server — reach for reqwest, hyper, or axum. No JSON — serde + serde_json. No regex — the regex crate (intentionally excluded to keep compile times low). No random number generation — rand. No date/time — chrono or time.

The pattern: std defines traits (Iterator, From, Display, Error), ecosystem crates implement them. This keeps the core stable and lets you swap implementations. serde's Serialize/Deserialize works across formats precisely because it's trait-based, not std-bundled.

One exception worth knowing: std::collections::HashMap uses a DoS-resistant hasher by default. If you need raw speed, swap to FxHashMap (rustc-hash) or AHashMap (ahash) — same API, explicit tradeoff.$escape$,
  $escape$use std::collections::HashMap;
use rustc_hash::FxHashMap; // cargo add rustc-hash

fn main() {
    // std HashMap — DoS-resistant (SipHash), slightly slower
    let mut std_map: HashMap<&str, u32> = HashMap::new();
    std_map.insert("latency_ms", 42);

    // FxHashMap — faster, not cryptographically safe
    let mut fast_map: FxHashMap<&str, u32> = FxHashMap::default();
    fast_map.insert("latency_ms", 42);

    // Same trait-based API — swap without changing call sites
    println!("{:?}", fast_map.get("latency_ms"));
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
