INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '80ff0477-e6cc-4740-9bb7-9c4730cf822d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Compiled Execution Model — Why Cold Starts Are Nearly Zero$escape$,
  $escape$Rust compiles directly to native machine code via LLVM — there's no VM, no interpreter, no JIT warmup phase. When your binary starts, it's already fully optimized for the target CPU. This makes Rust uniquely suited for latency-sensitive environments like AWS Lambda or Kubernetes sidecars where cold start time is a hard constraint.

Unlike Go's runtime (which includes a scheduler and GC bootstrap) or JVM-based services (which need class loading and JIT compilation before reaching peak throughput), a Rust binary's startup cost is essentially just OS process creation plus your own `main()` initialization code. A minimal Tokio-based HTTP server can be ready to accept connections in under 5ms.

This matters practically: Rust has no 'warmup cliff' — request latency at p99 on the first request is the same as the thousandth. The `#[inline]` and `#[cold]` attributes let you guide LLVM's branch prediction and inlining heuristics, pushing hot paths even further. `cargo build --release` enables full LTO and codegen-units=1 for maximum startup-time and throughput optimization.$escape$,
  $escape$// Cargo.toml profile for minimal cold start
// [profile.release]
// lto = true
// codegen-units = 1
// opt-level = 3
// strip = true

use tokio::net::TcpListener;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    // Binary is fully optimized at compile time — no JIT, no warmup
    let listener = TcpListener::bind("0.0.0.0:8080").await.unwrap();
    println!("Ready"); // This prints in <5ms on a Lambda cold start
    loop {
        let (_socket, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
