INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3f6e1601-b8b0-4bed-9cbc-b877e350c859',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust Unit Testing — Inline Modules, cargo test, and the #[cfg(test)] Pattern$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's test runner is built into `cargo` — no external framework needed. Unit tests live directly alongside production code inside a `#[cfg(test)]` module, meaning test code is compiled only during `cargo test`, keeping release binaries clean. Each `#[test]` fn runs in its own thread, so panics are caught without aborting the suite.

Use `assert_eq!` over `assert!(a == b)` — it prints both values on failure. For error paths, `#[should_panic(expected = "overflow")]` pins the panic message, preventing false passes from unrelated panics. Prefer returning `Result<(), E>` from tests instead of unwrapping: `?` propagates context and the failure output is far more readable.

Private functions are directly testable because the test module is a child of the same file — no need to expose internals via `pub`. Integration tests in `tests/` exercise only the public API and compile as separate crates. Run a single test with `cargo test test_name`, filter by module with `cargo test module::`, and capture stdout with `cargo test -- --nocapture`.$escape$,
  $escape$#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn parses_valid_semver() -> Result<(), String> {
        let v = parse_version("1.2.3")?;
        assert_eq!(v.major, 1);
        assert_eq!(v.minor, 2);
        Ok(())
    }

    #[test]
    #[should_panic(expected = "invalid")]
    fn rejects_malformed_version() {
        parse_version("not.a.version").unwrap();
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
