INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2b7336da-4321-4647-8520-c15cd72a661c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Security Triad: Memory Safety, Injection Prevention, and cargo audit$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's ownership model eliminates entire vulnerability classes by design — no buffer overflows, use-after-free, or null pointer dereferences in safe code. The borrow checker enforces these at compile time, not runtime. Treat `unsafe` blocks as trust boundaries: audit every one, keep them minimal, and wrap them in safe abstractions with a documented invariant.

For SQL injection, never interpolate user input into query strings. Use `sqlx` with compile-time verified parameterized queries via the `query!` or `query_as!` macros — the macro validates your SQL against a live database at compile time, catching both injection vectors and schema mismatches before you ship.

For dependency vulnerabilities, `cargo audit` cross-references your `Cargo.lock` against the RustSec Advisory Database. Integrate it into CI with `cargo audit --deny warnings` to fail fast. For stricter policy enforcement, add `cargo-deny` with a `deny.toml` that blocks unmaintained crates, disallowed licenses, and known CVEs. Run `cargo deny check` as a required CI gate — not a periodic afterthought.$escape$,
  $escape$use sqlx::PgPool;

// NEVER do this — injection risk:
// format!("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = {}", user_input)

async fn get_user(pool: &PgPool, user_id: i64) -> sqlx::Result<Option<User>> {
    sqlx::query_as!(
        User,
        "SELECT id, username, email FROM users WHERE id = $1",
        user_id  // bound parameter — SQL validated at compile time
    )
    .fetch_optional(pool)
    .await
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
