INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '774a8064-66c0-48b3-9d36-b251fc763b8b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust Horizontal Scaling — Send/Sync, Tokio's Thread Model, and Where Throughput Dies$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's horizontal scaling story is anchored in two compile-time traits: `Send` and `Sync`. Any type crossing a thread boundary must satisfy both — the compiler rejects data races before your service ever sees production load. Scale-out correctness is a type-system guarantee, not a runtime hope.

Tokio's work-stealing scheduler (`new_multi_thread`) maps M async tasks onto N OS threads (default N = logical CPU count). Unlike Go or JVM runtimes, there's no GC stop-the-world when a freshly scaled pod absorbs a traffic spike. Latency stays predictable under pressure because there's no allocator pausing the world.

The sharpest edge in the thread model: blocking calls inside `async fn` stall the executor thread entirely, collapsing throughput across all tasks sharing that worker. Offload CPU-bound or blocking I/O with `tokio::task::spawn_blocking`, which routes work to a dedicated thread pool capped separately from async workers.

For shared mutable state, prefer `tokio::sync::mpsc` channels over `Arc<Mutex<T>>`. Under high concurrency, mutex contention serializes tasks far more aggressively than benchmarks suggest — channels let each task own its data and communicate by value, keeping `Send` semantics and eliminating lock hot spots.$escape$,
  $escape$use tokio::sync::mpsc;

#[tokio::main(flavor = "multi_thread", worker_threads = 4)]
async fn main() {
    let (tx, mut rx) = mpsc::channel::<String>(1024);

    for i in 0..8 {
        let tx = tx.clone();
        tokio::spawn(async move {
            let result = tokio::task::spawn_blocking(move || format!("processed-{i}"))
                .await
                .unwrap();
            tx.send(result).await.unwrap();
        });
    }
    drop(tx);
    while let Some(msg) = rx.recv().await {
        println!("{msg}");
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
