INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a0e0a6d3-4c61-4d9c-9f5b-a7dc02b8665f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust's Ecosystem Maturity — How the Critical Path Stabilized$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's ecosystem has crossed the maturity threshold. crates.io hosts over 145,000 crates, and the critical path for backend work is now covered by battle-tested libraries. `serde` — 200M+ downloads — is the universal serialization layer, implemented across virtually every data-carrying crate via derive macros. `tokio` is the de facto async runtime, underpinning `axum`, `reqwest`, `tonic`, and `sqlx`. This convergence around a single runtime avoids the ecosystem fragmentation that plagued early async Rust.

Rust's edition system (2015 → 2018 → 2021) provides forward compatibility without breaking existing crates — your `Cargo.toml` declares the edition, the compiler handles the delta. The Rust Foundation, backed by Google, Microsoft, AWS, Meta, and Huawei, funds compiler and toolchain work. AWS ships Firecracker in Rust; Google has millions of lines in Android. These aren't experiments.

Weak spots remain: GUI frameworks are still fragmented, and `async fn` in traits only fully stabilized in 1.75. But for backend systems — HTTP servers, CLIs, networking, data pipelines — the ecosystem is production-grade. The `anyhow` + `thiserror` error handling story alone eliminated an entire class of ergonomics complaints.$escape$,
  $escape$use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use sqlx::PgPool;

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize, sqlx::FromRow)]
struct Article {
    id: i32,
    title: String,
    published: bool,
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let pool = PgPool::connect(&std::env::var("DATABASE_URL")?).await?;
    let rows: Vec<Article> =
        sqlx::query_as!(Article, "SELECT id, title, published FROM articles WHERE published = true")
            .fetch_all(&pool)
            .await?;
    println!("{}", serde_json::to_string_pretty(&rows)?);
    Ok(())
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
