INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'aad114e6-9705-4f0f-932d-6a06fecd2e0e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rust Ownership — Why &mut self Kills Disjoint Field Borrows$escape$,
  $escape$Rust's borrow checker tracks borrows at the field level when you access struct fields directly — two `&mut` borrows of disjoint fields coexist in the same scope without issue. The moment you call a method taking `&mut self`, that granularity collapses: the entire struct is consumed by one mutable borrow, blocking any further borrows of its fields until the method returns.

This breaks a common pattern: passing `self.field_a` as an argument to a `&mut self` method. The compiler rejects it even when the fields don't overlap, because it can't prove disjointness through an opaque method boundary.

The fix is to replace the method with a free function (or a method on a sub-struct) that takes individual `&mut` references explicitly. This exposes the borrow boundaries so the checker can verify non-aliasing statically.

`slice::split_at_mut` is the canonical stdlib example — it cannot be written in safe Rust because the compiler can't prove two halves of a single slice are non-overlapping through a function call. The implementation uses `unsafe` internally to assert that invariant manually.$escape$,
  $escape$struct Parser {
    buf: Vec<u8>,
    pos: usize,
}

impl Parser {
    // Fails: `&mut self` borrows all of `self`,
    // so `self.buf` and `self.pos` can't be re-borrowed
    // fn advance(&mut self) -> u8 { consume(&self.buf, &mut self.pos) }
}

// Fix: free function takes disjoint refs — checker can verify non-aliasing
fn advance(buf: &[u8], pos: &mut usize) -> u8 {
    let byte = buf[*pos];
    *pos += 1;
    byte
}

fn main() {
    let mut p = Parser { buf: vec![10, 20, 30], pos: 0 };
    // Direct field access gives disjoint borrows — compiles fine
    let b = advance(&p.buf, &mut p.pos);
    println!("{b}"); // 10
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
